<div class="text">
<p>
For those debating this important roleplaying game rules questions:
</p><p>
You read the face facing the floor, as if gravity had been inverted and the die was simply resting on the ceiling plane.
</p><p>
This follows from the cosmology of <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spelljammer#Gravity_and_air">Spelljammer</a></i>, which is the best and last word in how gravity should work in a game universe. (Although of course if the die is sufficiently cocked, you have to reroll. That goes without saying.)
</p><p>
<i>[Reminder: Our guest commentators have not seen</i> Rogue One. <i>Part of the fun is seeing how their untainted impressions re-interpret the movie through the lens of our comic.]</i>
</p>

<div class="keybounce">
<p>
Ah, Sally, Sally, Sally.
</p><p>
You are firing into a melee, without specifying who you're shooting at.
</p><p>
— Keybounce
</p>
</div>

<div class="aurilee">
<p>
While I have never seen dice stuck in the ceiling, I did once have to locate a die that landed in the middle of a large cluster of potted cacti. Also a domino tile. Also a meeple. Also a Hot Wheels car. I have become very good at extracting cactus needles from my hand.
</p><p>
I highly recommend not playing games in a room with large cacti, by the way.
</p><p>
— aurilee
</p>
</div>

<h3>Transcript</h3>
<p>
<b>GM:</b> You find an Imperial shuttle.<br>
<b>K-2SO:</b> You know how to fly these things?<br>
<b>Bodhi:</b> I sure do!<br>
<b>K-2SO:</b> And I sure know how to shoot these weapons! Let's go!<br>
<b>GM:</b> You scan the area and find Cassian and Bria, being chased by troopers.<br>
<b>[SFX]:</b> Pow! Pow! Pow! Pow! Pow!<br>
<b>K-2SO:</b> Ha ha! Take that! And that!<br>
<b>[SFX]:</b> Pow!<br>
<b>K-2SO:</b> And that!!<br>
<b>[SFX]:</b> Pow! Pow!<br>
<b>[SFX]:</b> Kaboom!<br>
<b>GM:</b> I've seen dice on the floor before, but this is the first time I've seen one stuck in the ceiling.
</p>
